metadata.name: Sketches:Pairs of Tails:Majestic Creatures #29
metadata.description:
Addendum to Annuls of WorSAGE (the Worshipful Society of Adventurers and Generative Explorers) XXVII.Vol.2048

There is a significantly common phenomena in which Pairs of "Tails of Majestic Creatures" are found together. Various sketches of these "Pairs" have been collated and are available, free of charge, the collectors of the initial Tails of Majestic Creatures collection based upon a recently taken collection registry snapshot. 

These sketches are available on a one per collector basis and for a limited time only after which they will no longer be accessible.

The sketches come in 2 forms - an ink and color style, and a pencil style - for which different colored paper has been used.

The digitally minded can press s to get a 5000x3000 download of a sketch.

metadata.name: PRINTERS #17
metadata.description:
Generative animated artwork made using shader feedback and pixel quantization.

PRINTERS is a study of rasterized type and bitmap imagery. It builds on the tradition of ASCII and typographic art, blending dithering techniques with chunky, pixelated glyphs. Here, the movement and blending of color is interpreted as a monochrome composition of recognizable pixel patterns taken from legacy video games and operating systems. What appears as typography is actually a custom set of 8x8 pixel patterns rendered in a GLSL shader that produces a conceptual tension between low-res graphics and high-power GPU computation.

PRINTERS is designed to be both viewed on a screen and printed on office paper with a home/office inkjet printer.

Press 'i' to invert the colors.
Press '1', '2', or '3' to scale the bitmap glyphs.
Press 'g' to download a looping animated GIF (90 frames).
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Press 'f' (or double tap in mobile) to stretch to full screen.
Made with vanilla javascript and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #20
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Scattered Pathways #82
metadata.description:
"Scattered Pathways" studies pathfinding on a grid. I enjoy watching the sketch find and fill the available spaces. I hope you enjoy this one too!

Royalties Splits:
50% Donation to minter

Features:
Two different sizes: 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
@liamegan1/fxhash-helpers
@altesc/stdio

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Timelines #252
metadata.description:
#fxhashturnsone - Happy Birthday fxhash!

Some days are busy and some are quiet.
Some weeks go fast and some go slow.
Some months are good, some are bad.
Here we are: talking about, looking at, making, collecting, buying, selling, trading and obsessing about generative crypto art.
Artists, collectors, artworks, opinions, trends, ideas; continuously overlapping, intertwining, influencing, burying, surfacing, remembering and forgetting.
We keep going, in search of the next.

This algorithm draws lines horizontally across the canvas.
There can be 12, 52 or 365 lines.
The lines can be straight, curvy, or both.
Straight lines can be angled or horizontal.
The line thickness can be random from 1-365, or all 12, 52 or 365 pts.
And there are 12 colour palettes.

Inspired by Sol LeWitt’s Wavy Brushstrokes work and the fxhash tweet prompting “365 editions” a week ago.

Follow me on twitter @fauxjebus

~—~—~—~—~—~—~—~—~

Features:
F - Fullscreen
S - Save image
2/4/6/8/0 - Change image resolution (press number key and then reload in live view)

metadata.name: Make-believe #4
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: CHX-1 #170
metadata.description:
Glitching pixels like it’s 1999.

Inspired by 90’s digital aesthetics, CHX-1 takes a random selection of GAN seeds, combines them in unique ways, and processes them –individually and as a group– with a series of glitching dithering algorithms. Generating fun, original, colorful artworks. Millions of possibilities. Have fun!

<<< Base seeds generated offline using personal styleGAN2-ADA models. Image processing and combinations done generatively by the CHX-1 algorithm >>>

GAN –> p5js –> Blockchain


• Artworks can take a few seconds to load when running live code.

• Press “s” (when "open live" is active) to save a PNG image.


Copyright (©) 2022 Thomas Noya
Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Sands of Time #90
metadata.description:
We've been recently inspired to do this work while being on vacation, in one the most vibrant cities in the world, in the hot pot and intermixture of cultures, terrains and soundscapes. Borrowing the metaphors of sand, from Negarestani's "Cyclonopedia", and of time from "Chronosis", these living substances, we wanted to represent some of the vibes, that have been implanted into our gritty enduring nomadic existence.

This work was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine
- #Tezos4Iran

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

November, 2022
Julia V & YulikolaY
